      "\n  intro x hx\n  have h₁ : x ∈ V(G, M) := hx\n  have h₂ : x ∈ V(G, M ∆ E(P)) := by\n    have h₃ : V(G, M) ⊆ V(G) := by\n      intro x hx\n      exact hx.2\n    have h₄ : x ∈ V(G) := h₃ h₁\n    have h₅ : x ∈ V(G, M ∆ E(P)) := by\n      simp only [Set.mem_symmDiff, Set.mem_insert_iff, Set.mem_singleton_iff] at *\n      have h₆ : x ∈ V(G, M) := h₁\n      by_cases h₇ : x ∈ V(G, E(P))\n      · -- If x is in V(G, E(P)), then it is in V(G, M ∆ E(P))\n        simp_all [Set.mem_symmDiff]\n        <;>\n        (try contradiction) <;>\n        (try aesop) <;>\n        (try {\n          cases h with\n          | intro hP h₁ =>\n            simp_all [isAugPath_iff, isAltPath_iff, isPath_iff]\n            <;>\n            (try contradiction) <;>\n            (try aesop)\n        })\n      · -- If x is not in V(G, E(P)), then it is in V(G, M ∆ E(P))\n        simp_all [Set.mem_symmDiff]\n        <;>\n        (try contradiction) <;>\n        (try aesop)\n    exact h₅\n  exact h₂",
      "\n  intro v hv\n  haveI : Inhabited β := inferInstance\n  haveI : Inhabited α := inferInstance\n  simp only [hM, Set.subset_def, V, mem_iUnion, exists_prop] at h hv ⊢\n  simp_all [P.toWedgeSet, Set.mem_symmDiff, Set.mem_singleton_iff]\n  <;> tauto",
      "\n  intro x hx\n  have h' : x ∈ V(G, M) := hx\n  have h₁ : x ∈ V(G) := h'.1\n  have h₂ : x ∈ V(G(M)) := h'.2\n  have h₃ : x ∈ V(G, symmDiff M P.edgeSet) := by\n    simp_all [V, symmDiff, Set.mem_union, Set.mem_setOf_eq]\n    <;>\n    (try tauto) <;>\n    (try aesop) <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        aesop\n      }) <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        tauto\n      })\n  exact h₃",
      "\n  intro x hx\n  by_cases hxP : x ∈ V(G, P) <;>\n    simp_all [Set.mem_inter_iff, Set.mem_diff, Set.mem_singleton_iff]\n  <;>\n    (try tauto) <;>\n    (try {\n      obtain ⟨v, hv⟩ := h.toIsAltPath.toIsPath.exists_realization\n      simp_all [WList.mem_realization]\n      <;>\n        tauto\n    }) <;>\n    (try {\n      have h₁ := h.toIsAltPath.toIsPath\n      have h₂ := h.toIsAltPath.mem_matching\n      simp_all [WList.mem_edgeSet, WList.mem_realization, Realization.mem_of_iff]\n      <;>\n        aesop\n    })\n  <;>\n    (try {\n      exfalso\n      have h₁ := h.toIsAltPath.toIsPath\n      have h₂ := h.toIsAltPath.mem_matching\n      simp_all [WList.mem_edgeSet, WList.mem_realization, Realization.mem_of_iff]\n      <;>\n        aesop\n    })\n  <;>\n    (try {\n      have h₁ := h.toIsAltPath.toIsPath\n      have h₂ := h.toIsAltPath.mem_matching\n      simp_all [WList.mem_edgeSet, WList.mem_realization, Realization.mem_of_iff]\n      <;>\n        aesop\n    })\n  <;>\n    (try tauto)\n  <;>\n    (try {\n      exfalso\n      have h₁ := h.toIsAltPath.toIsPath\n      have h₂ := h.toIsAltPath.mem_matching\n      simp_all [WList.mem_edgeSet, WList.mem_realization, Realization.mem_of_iff]\n      <;>\n        aesop\n    })\n  <;>\n    (try {\n      have h₁ := h.toIsAltPath.toIsPath\n      have h₂ := h.toIsAltPath.mem_matching\n      simp_all [WList.mem_edgeSet, WList.mem_realization, Realization.mem_of_iff]\n      <;>\n        aesop\n    })",
      "is incident",
      "\n   Thus, the rigorous proof steps should be something like this:\n   - Assume `v ∈ V(G, M)`.\n   - There is some `e ∈ M` with `v ∈ V(G, e)`.\n   - If `e ∉ P.edgeSet`, then `e ∈ M ∆ P.edgeSet` and we’re done.\n   - Else, `e ∈ P.edgeSet` and `v ∈ V(G, e)`:\n     - Since `v ∈ V(G, M)`, it cannot be `P`'s endpoints (`P`’s endpoints are not in `V(G,",
      "",
      "\n\nYet",
      "this is not directly helpful. Maybe it's better to look at the Lean definitions and try to find some lemmas about the symmetric difference.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps `V(G, M) ⊆ V(G, E(P)) ∪ V(G, M \\ E(P)) ⊆ V(G, M Δ E(P))` because if `M Δ E(P)` is `(M \\ E(P)) ∪ (E(P) \\ M)`.\n\nBut perhaps in the second case, if `v` is covered by an edge in `E(P)`, then it is also covered by `M Δ E(P)` because that edge is in `E(P)` but not in `M`.\n\nBut in the first case, if the edge is in `M` but not in `E(P)`, it is in `M Δ E(P)` and `v` is covered.\n\nBut we need to ensure that every `v ∈ V(G, M)` is covered by an edge in `E(P)` or by an edge in `M` not in `E(P)`.\n\nIn the case where `v` is covered by `e ∈ M`, if `e ∉ E(P)`, then `e ∈ M Δ E(P)` and `v` is covered.\nIf `e ∈ E(P)`, then we need that at least one of the adjacent edges in `P` is not in `M` and covers `v`.\n\nBut in Lean, `IsAltPath.mem_matching_iff` says that for any two consecutive edges in `P`, they alternate membership in `M`. But in particular, for every edge in `P`, if it is in `M`, the next and previous edges are not in `M`. \n\nTherefore, if `e ∈ M ∩ E(P)`, then the edges adjacent to `e` in `P` are not in `M`. \n\nSo, suppose `v` is covered by `e ∈ M`, and `e ∈ P`. Then, `e` has two endpoints: `v` and some other vertex. At least one of these two vertices (unless they are the same) is part of another edge in `P`. \n\nBut perhaps it's easier to think about `P` as a sequence `v_0 e_1 v_1 ... v_{k-1} e_k v_k`, where `e_i ∈ M ↔ e_{i+1} ∉ M` (if we interpret `e_0` as not existing).\n\nThen, given `e ∈ M ∩ P`, `e` is `e_i` for some `i`, and then `e_{i+1} ∉ M`. \n\nBut `e_{i+1}` connects `v_i` and `v_{i+1}`. If `e` connects `v_{i-1}` and `v_i`, then `v_i` is an endpoint of both `e_i` and `e_{i+1}`. \n\nThus, `v_i` is covered by `e_{i+1}` which is in `E(P)` but not in `M`, hence in `M Δ E(P)`.\n\nSimilarly, if `e` is the first edge in `P`, say `e_1`, then `v_0` is not in `V(M)` (from `IsAugPath`), but `v_0` is covered by `e_1 ∈ M`, and we have `e_2 ∉ M` (because `e_1 ∈ M`). Then `v_1` is covered by `e_2` which is in `E(P)` but not `M`, so `v_1 ∈ V(G, M Δ E(P))`. \n\nBut `v_0` is covered by `e_1`, which is in `M` and in `E(P)`, so it is not in `M Δ E(P)`, unless we have another edge in `M` covering `v_0` which is not in `E(P)`.\n\nBut we are assuming `v_0 ∉ V(M)` (by `IsAugPath`), so perhaps `v_0` is not",
      "",
      "\n  intro x hx\n  have h₁ : x ∈ V(G, M ∆ E(P)) := by\n    -- Since x is in V(G, M), we need to show it is also in V(G, M ∆ E(P))\n    -- x is in V(G, M) implies x is in V(G) and there exists an edge in M incident to x\n    -- We need to show that x is in V(G) and there exists an edge in M ∆ E(P) incident to x\n    -- Since x is in V(G, M), it is already in V(G)\n    -- We need to find an edge in M ∆ E(P) incident to x\n    have h₂ : x ∈ V(G) := by\n      -- x is in V(G, M), so it is in V(G)\n      have h₃ : x ∈ V(G, M) := hx\n      simp only [VGM] at h₃ ⊢\n      aesop\n    -- We need to show that there exists an edge in M ∆ E(P) incident to x\n    -- Since x is in V(G, M), there exists an edge in M incident to x\n    -- We need to check if this edge is in M ∆ E(P)\n    simp only [VGM] at hx ⊢\n    aesop\n  exact h₁",
