1. The proof directly uses set membership and subset relations to establish that `V(G, M)` is contained in `V(G, symmDiff M P.edgeSet)`.
2. We split the proof into two cases based on whether `v ∈ V(G, P.edgeSet)` or not.
3. The first case (`v ∈ V(G, P.edgeSet)`) relies on the fact that if `v ∈ P.edgeSet`, then it will also be in the symmetric difference `symmDiff M P.edgeSet` if it is not already in `M`.
4. The second case (`v ∉ V(G, P.edgeSet)`) uses `v ∈ V(G, M)` (by hypothesis) to deduce that `v` will trivially be in `symmDiff M P.edgeSet` because it is in `M` but not in `P.edgeSet`.
5. The `aesop` tactic handles the logical deductions in the second case by exploiting the symmetric difference's set operations.

